high on a barren mountaintop 
overlooking the dead sea aisha halifa listens to the evening 
newscast on the persian gulf crisis on a transistor radio and fears 
for her children 
she knows that no matter what happens next in the confrontation 
with iraq they are going to suffer the economic consequences of 
the crisis 
jordan its economy already in perilous shape and now burdened 
with hundreds of thousands of refugees is staring disaster in the 
face 
rebecca salti utahborn director of save the children in 
jordan said that even if the crisis does not flare into war 
jordanian children will be going hungry within a matter of months 
were just trying to figure out how to get through the 
winter she said its going to be tough there will be food 
shortages or the inability to buy food by late winter or early 
spring 
the crisis has devastated aisha halifas family in beni hamide 
25 miles southwest of amman she and about 600 other women in a 
cluster of bedouin villages in the mountains weave rugs for sale to 
tourists but the visitors arent coming any more because of the 
fear of war 
her family raises goats and has a few olive trees but it was 
the income from her weaving that paid for secondhand clothes 
school supplies and medical care for her children 
until early august she received some money from her 23yearold 
son working in kuwait but he fled the iraqi invasion and came 
home along with 120000 of his countrymen suddenly poor and 
unemployed 
before the crisis unemployment in jordan was at 15 percent 
now theres almost no chance that aishas son or husband will find 
work 
families wont have money to take their children to the 
doctor everything will go into food they wont be able to buy 
shoes erasers or notebooks to keep the kids in school ms salti 
said 
already ms halifa cant afford a visit to the clinic for her 
son who has a scalp disease within weeks there wont be enough 
money for school supplies the girls will be forced to drop out so 
their brothers can go on a little while longer by spring there 
might not even be food 
even professionals people who have studied and live in amman 
are having trouble now she said tugging at a steelgray curl 
falling from under her brown headscarf if they cant make it 
how can we i dont know what were going to do im frightened for 
my children 
the un international childrens emergency fund is worried too 
children will be the first victims the hardest hit and the 
ones most overlooked by the international community said nigel 
fischer unicefs deputy regional director in amman 
the impact will extend far beyond jordan leila bisharat 
unicefs chief of programs for the middle east says similar 
hardships will confront children in impoverished nations whose 
fathers once sent paychecks home from kuwait 
every one of the wage earners whove fled once sent money home 
to support an extended family kuwait was their one lifeline and 
now thats gone she said 
bangladesh sri lanka india and the philippines are 
illprepared to absorb the hundreds of thousands of returning 
refugees or help their families 
for these countries the months ahead appear bleak the persian 
gulf standoff is pushing their already fragile economies closer to 
disaster 
we have all over the world four to six million children wholl 
now have no source of income mrs bisharat said were all 
holding our breath for what could be a catastrophe 
jordan alone will lose 400 million in workers pay this year 
the finance ministry says the number of people living below the 
world bankdefined poverty line of 1600 a year could jump from 25 
percent to 40 percent by spring experts say 
half of jordans 31 million people are under 15 years old milk 
is already being rationed and unicef says it has already seen a 
slight increase in malnutrition in the poorest of ammans 
neighborhoods packed with palestinian refugees 
these families were managing to feed their kids well the kids 
were looking healthy all across jordan we had just sort of made 
it said mrs salti 
the children were immunized they were in school the girls 
were being educated and they were just beginning to bloom in every 
way jordan was coming into its own 
now she said well be lucky if these children can pull 
through 
