boris yeltsin president of the russian republic 
was back on a collision course with mikhail s gorbachev saturday 
as he challenged the soviet leaders request for new emergency 
powers to rescue the economy 
yeltsin and gorbachev have waged a threeyear political feud 
that has complicated gorbachevs efforts to implement urgent 
economic reform 
in a statement read on the nightly television news program 
vremya the countrys most widely watched program yeltsin and 
other leaders of russias legislature called gorbachevs request 
for expanded powers unacceptable 
the leaders vowed to take all necessary measures to defend the 
sovereignty and constitutional order of russia 
gorbachev asked the national legislature friday to expand his 
powers in order to begin an economic rescue plan without having to 
go through the tedious process of seeking lawmakers approval at 
each step 
gorbachev seeks the authority to issue decrees on property 
management of the economy prices and law enforcement 
the national supreme soviet would have the power to recommend 
gorbachev revoke or modify the decrees the supreme soviet is 
scheduled to vote on the rquest monday the same day it is to 
choose from among three economic plans 
yeltsin fears gorbachev seeks the power to introduce 
presidential rule in sovereign republics and disband their 
governments that request is not contained in gorbachevs 
resolution but apparently was inferred from his comments to the 
supreme soviet 
gorbachev said he needed the extra authority because the dire 
state of the economy requires extreme action the powers would be 
used to implement one of the three plans to switch the soviet union 
to a market economy 
yeltsins celebrated clashes with gorbachev date back to 
criticism of reforms at a communist party meeting in 1987 the 
attacks have escalated since yeltsin was elected president of 
russia in may 
the two politicians the most prominent in the country have 
most recently battled over the rights of republics the russian 
parliament has declared that its laws take priority over those 
passed by the soviet parliament 
